IPURN622AL020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Health Care and Social Assistance: Hospitals, Except Psychiatric and Substance Abuse Hospitals (NAICS 622A) in the United States
IPURN622AL020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPURN622AL020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Health Care and Social Assistance

IPURN62151L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Health Care and Social Assistance: Medical and Diagnostic Laboratories (NAICS 62151) in the United States
IPURN62151L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPURN62151L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Health Care and Social Assistance

IPURN62151U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Health Care and Social Assistance: Medical and Diagnostic Laboratories (NAICS 62151) in the United States
IPURN62151U110000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPURN62151U110000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Health Care and Social Assistance

IPURN62151U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Health Care and Social Assistance: Medical and Diagnostic Laboratories (NAICS 62151) in the United States

Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
